			&nbsp;<a href="JavaScript:openWindow('pop_mail.asp?id=3948')"><img src="icon_email.gif" height="15" width="15" alt="Email Poster" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        &nbsp;<a href="JavaScript:openWindow('pop_messengers.asp?mode=ICQ&amp;ICQ=43751860&amp;M_NAME=Alaaraaf')"><img src="http://online.mirabilis.com/scripts/online.dll?icq=43751860&amp;img=5" height="15" width="15" alt="Send Alaaraaf an ICQ Message" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        &nbsp;<a href="post.asp?method=ReplyQuote&amp;REPLY_ID=40114&amp;TOPIC_ID=4836&amp;FORUM_ID=13&amp;CAT_ID=2&amp;Forum_Title=Newbie+Land&amp;Topic_Title=Does+this+work%3F&amp;M="><img src="icon_reply_topic.gif" height="15" width="15" alt="Reply with Quote" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        <hr noshade size="2" color="#545A7D">
        
         <BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=2 face="Verdana" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>Root has a variable duration (or mobs check resistance multiple times, I am not sure which) which leads to early breaks.<BR><hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana" size=2 id=quote></P><P>I'm pretty sure this is a resistance check each tick, rather than a random duration.  This is why:<BR><ul><li><b>Resistance check:</b><BR>If the mob checks against it's own resistance, the likelyhood of Root breaking should be the same as the likelihood of an outright resist at the initial casting.  Thus, if a mob resists Root 1/10, the probability of Root breaking at any given tick is 10%.  The significant part of this, is that a mob that resists Root <b>very</b> rarely should not break Root prematurely very often.</li><BR><li><b>Random duration:</b><BR>If the duration of Root is randomised, the resistance of the Rooted mob are completely irrelevant.  The upshot of this ould be that even if you Root a green mob, known to have feeble resistances, the Root might well <b>still</b> fade prematurely.</li></ul></P><P>So, some evidence...</P><P>Sun Revenants are <b>really</b> Root resistant.  Root will normally be resisted more times than not and when it sticks, they shrug it off in one, or two ticks!  <i>(Hungry Earth works reasonably well, but even so, not in the spectacular fashion in which it can normally be relied upon for.  (Whack Xalgoz with HE and watch your pet beat the bejeesus out of him.  HE will usually stick even through this!))</i>  If Root were of random duration, the duration should conform to either a straight line, or a Bell curve, depending on how it is calculated.  It does neither.  It breaks early almost every time.  The rapid failure of the Root supports the resistance check possibility!</P><P>Conversely, if you Root yourself a green mob, and the random duration theory is correct, it should break at it's predetermined time, rarely running it's full duration.  However, it is clear that, unless the Root is disrupted in some way, this is not usually the case.  The regularity of a full duration Root, when cast on a low level, or low resistance mob again supports the resistance check theory.</P><P>Far too much thought on something pointless!  *Grin*</P><P>Anywho...</P><P>AlAaraaf.</P><P><BR> <a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height="15" width="15" border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
      </tr>

